<Cartography
  desk="data"
  figNumber="I"
  plateTitle="The Extradition Atlas — anchored on the United States"
  kicker="Data · Cartography · Issue 01"
  headline="The 78 countries that will not send you home."
  emphasis={{ type: 'circled', word: '78 countries' }}
  standfirst="Every extradition treaty on Earth, mapped. Select an anchor country — and the reader can see who it can call on, and who it can't."
  meta={{
    author: 'Ollie Inkwell',
    datePublished: '2026-04-19',
    displayDate: '19 April 2026',
    readMinutes: 12,
    formatLabel: 'Interactive map',
  }}
  sourceLine="Sources: US Department of State (18 U.S.C. § 3181); UK Home Office and NCA TCA guidance; Eurojust EAW data; national extradition acts for Australia, Canada, Russia, China, and the UAE; public-record compilations. Treaty status for some smaller states is inferred from legacy instruments and may have been superseded by domestic law. For illustration, not legal advice."
>
  <!-- Per-piece stamp: a suitcase for the Extradition Atlas.
       Bickford-Smith's "one motif per piece" move.
       Social-card version lives in src/pieces/extradition-atlas.ts (stampSvg). -->
  <svg slot="stamp" viewBox="0 0 30 22" aria-hidden="true">
    <g stroke="#111111" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
      <rect x="2" y="7" width="26" height="13" rx="0.5"/>
      <path d="M10 7 V3.5 h10 V7"/>
      <line x1="15" y1="11" x2="15" y2="16"/>
    </g>
  </svg>

  <!-- Short plate-intro prose — sits in the right gutter beside the map. -->
  <Fragment slot="plate-intro">
    <p>Extradition is the quiet infrastructure of cross-border enforcement. A treaty obliges one state to surrender a wanted person to another; without one, the receiving state is under no duty to help.</p>
    <p>The United States has bilateral treaties with <strong>117</strong> countries. That leaves <strong>78</strong> where no such obligation exists — the map is thinnest where the headlines are loudest.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- Long prose body (default slot) — 300–500 word SEO section. -->
  <h2>Reluctance is its own category</h2>
  <p>
    Having a treaty isn't the same as honouring it. Several of the United States' formal partners — Cuba, Bolivia, Ecuador, Switzerland, Nicaragua, Venezuela — refuse extradition as a rule, citing national laws that bar handing over their own citizens, political-offence exceptions, or plain diplomatic disagreement. The "reluctant" layer on this map is small but important: it separates the treaty-shaped hole from the genuine-hole, and flags the cases where legal paperwork exists but no one's coming home.
  </p>
  <h2>Havens, and the shape of flight</h2>
  <p>
    Toggle the "Highlight fugitive havens" layer and the map changes shape. A haven is any country with no meaningful extradition relationship to the anchor — by law, by politics, or by practice. These are the destinations fugitives from Western states tend to choose: UAE, Russia, Venezuela, parts of the Caucasus and South-East Asia. Flight routes cluster around them, which is one reason tax havens and extradition havens overlap more than the coincidence would suggest.
  </p>
  <p>
    Click a country that is itself one of the anchors — the United States, the UK, the EU, Australia, Canada, Russia, China, the UAE — and the map re-centres on it. The network is not symmetrical: the US reaches far, Russia reaches only through the CIS, and the EU's European Arrest Warrant gives 27 states something closer to a single jurisdiction than a web of treaties.
  </p>
  <p>
    What the map shows, in the end, is a legal surface pocked with absences. <em>— Ollie</em>
  </p>
</Cartography>
